<subSubSection id="683A22618079CFF578C1757B1D590EFB" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" type="etimology">
<paragraph id="C5EED571677B6B1EC77DFA97C8447254" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Etimology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="475A7DD5FCE73FB326114E00F40FBE01" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName id="886B4028556CC13BE0124251D1ACB841" authorityName="Zuluaga &amp; Munoz-Castillo" authorityYear="2019" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Chlorospatha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Chlorospatha silverstonei" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="silverstonei">
<emphasis id="B6273B4887F6352BC34CBEB8E9E67216" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Chlorospatha silverstonei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is named in honor of Dr. Phillip Silverstone-Sopkin (1939-2018), an American botanist who lived and worked in Colombia for 39 years. He was a faculty member at Universidad del Valle until 2014 and an 
<emphasis id="9904EFC4AEF7DAEA9192BB91682F5B16" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">ad Honorem</emphasis>
professor since 2015. Additionally, he was the director of the herbarium Luis Sigifredo Espinal Tascon at the same University for 17 years. Dr. Silverstone-Sopkin collected more than 13000 botanical specimens, especially from the department of Valle del Cauca, and carried out several explorations in the region where this species was found.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2052615AC68625B04BB616D5AD5321DB" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="72FC9E7AEBE0455CA30E36B0BAECA322" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8A998532D1DA0E0843D174C538B33D63" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName id="466D237B47F5E62B4A6516B029846610" authorityName="Zuluaga &amp; Munoz-Castillo" authorityYear="2019" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Chlorospatha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Chlorospatha silverstonei" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="silverstonei">
<emphasis id="0A29E09A1F1B6799F2186E79136B4BF4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Chlorospatha silverstonei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to the western slopes of the Colombian Andes, along the border between the departments of Valle del Cauca and 
<normalizedToken id="B3F1440DC3A706AC5017AD10A67A3751" originalValue="Chocó">Choco</normalizedToken>
. It grows in cloud forests between 1900 and 2300 m. It has been collected in two natural reserves, &quot;Cerro El 
<normalizedToken id="E28D0E521E149BDE59AAB9F60F22F553" originalValue="Inglés”">Ingles&quot;</normalizedToken>
and &quot;Alto Galapagos&quot; (
<figureCitation id="0959557F8ED9AA50A2A4E9F944F23B0D" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Distribution map of Chlorospatha minima (star) and C. silverstonei (circle)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.135.38050.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/353742" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" tableDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.135.38050.figure1">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), where it has been found widespread in the dark understory, with high humidity and, sometimes, flooded ground. This species has been recorded flowering in October and January. Information about pollination is still lacking but we observed individuals of a species of 
<taxonomicName id="FF4902C3EC3CF28B3CD61179483D04C6" family="Brachonidae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="tribe" tribe="Brachonidae">Brachonidae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="09CD98DADAFC4D51F51A5699F6B2686B" authorityName="Engler" authorityYear="1878" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Chlorospatha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
) visiting the inflorescence during female anthesis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FE368556B481ED3A2818EF0B5F318519" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="ADFFBE11D6D67213E968D16FE1A28507" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0A8DBF685066C4752A74D1C3A5EEB0D5" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName id="4B06E774CDD2BFABBCE9ACD49FB09008" authorityName="Zuluaga &amp; Munoz-Castillo" authorityYear="2019" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Chlorospatha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Chlorospatha silverstonei" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="silverstonei">
<emphasis id="0FD1D384330E10DCDC30798DE5BA1912" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Chlorospatha silverstonei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been found in two localities along the 
<normalizedToken id="896F3FBF3A0BAAC88F126B4644348B5F" originalValue="Serranía">Serrania</normalizedToken>
de los Paraguas mountain range, with an estimated extent of occurrence larger than 38000 km2. In these two localities there are several populations of this species with abundant individuals; therefore, 
<taxonomicName id="4CC4C8AA3B7297DF14146C27DB92040D" genus="C." lsidName="C. silverstonei" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="silverstonei">
<emphasis id="28277CEECC4A16FE61143EEB8096F9A3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">C. silverstonei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is preliminary categorized as Least Concern (LC), according to the IUCN criteria (
<bibRefCitation id="A282BA796B69886E19194CEAC911EFF5" author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" refId="B7" refString="IUCN, 2012. IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. Second edition. Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK, iv + 32 pp." title="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. Second edition. Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK, iv + 32 pp." year="2012">IUCN 2012</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="B9725A036E25CEE99FCB1191072281C8" author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B8" refString="IUCN, 2017. Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 13. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee. http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" title="Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 13. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee." url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2017">2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D5617C5D02400637ECE486C1FFE0E5FA" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="46D16D238CD414B348263857A33855C7" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="539DEFEC0D15F72797312CF64F2D2F83" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName id="C9BAA20D962E0046064F583749B99DF9" authorityName="Zuluaga &amp; Munoz-Castillo" authorityYear="2019" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Chlorospatha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Chlorospatha silverstonei" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="silverstonei">
<emphasis id="EABE8D404874386AD1FEF528F804F198" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Chlorospatha silverstonei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="55E426D7D1BC65F5B32BAD7D09CD36DF" genus="C." lsidName="C. minima" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="minima">
<emphasis id="17BFC5010FFC5B17F7B723DDE1238246" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">C. minima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="91342179BFA9766FF006AE08FDBECB0D" genus="C." lsidName="C. longipoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="longipoda">
<emphasis id="F3AE8600CBB6123DC973B1D20B9BA0A0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">C. longipoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="8A926CA9323B2DFF16DAD24DED4A099C" genus="C." lsidName="C. hannoniae" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="hannoniae">
<emphasis id="31A2A93B8F43183E307D9DA54CA0681F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">C. hannoniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="CE724E8E7ABE67D08AA9504C10747243" genus="C." lsidName="C. boosii" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="boosii">
<emphasis id="6D458F2E3332FA15C147C4C9B86A0C85" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">C. boosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it differs from these four species in having fewer leaves (1-3 vs. 2-14) (Table 
<tableCitation id="F895D3FCFA4EF3DA6AC768D4121FBC86" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Morphological comparison of Chlorospatha minima, C. silverstonei, C. longipoda, C. hannoniae and C. boosii." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/63FE85514411458DC896557368499C5B" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" tableUuid="63FE85514411458DC896557368499C5B">1</tableCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="C1F0B39480ECA242A0E28166C48085B6" authorityName="Zuluaga &amp; Munoz-Castillo" authorityYear="2019" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Chlorospatha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Chlorospatha silverstonei" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="silverstonei">
<emphasis id="71CFC12CAE1608B438123927D2B02A35" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Chlorospatha silverstonei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="1D5B6E03309D63684C5723D1268FA73A" genus="C." lsidName="C. minima" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="minima">
<emphasis id="2226DBDEF644B2E16AF0C7B3730CEA07" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">C. minima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having 1-3 leaves (vs. 2-5 in 
<taxonomicName id="B2FDA8C84FF929D9BA571208D516BD81" genus="C." lsidName="C. minima" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="minima">
<emphasis id="BA6FDDBF70F382B578F36008015B8491" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">C. minima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), longer petioles, 15.2
<normalizedToken id="9D4B172F5DD0A5D3C8613AF427BE4BAD" originalValue="–46.8(–">-46.8(-</normalizedToken>
52.4) cm long (vs. 8.3-28.2 cm), that are irregularly dark purple-mottled with longitudinal dark purple lines (vs. green with darker transverse markings), blade broadly ovate to rounded (vs. broadly triangular-ovate), two collective veins (vs. three), fertile staminate portion slightly conical (vs. cylindrical), infructescence 18.5-32.6 
<normalizedToken id="A78306E6D07031175FFE70E3650ACA6F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4.8-10.3 mm (vs. 25.5 
<normalizedToken id="CA4848C2A5AD9C3CAEF2646AF350233F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8.0 mm) and seeds 1.5-2.0 
<normalizedToken id="153D31500605ED5C5E13F4D06354AF4D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.9-1.2 mm (vs. 1.2-1.5 
<normalizedToken id="9D39C985F455550468C770511A5221F4" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.7-0.9 mm). Finally, 
<taxonomicName id="9031C55D0FEE9DFD27B15675487EDC27" genus="C." lsidName="C. silverstonei" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="silverstonei">
<emphasis id="DD1459231B005479C137C016385C86CC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">C. silverstonei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="F04D9026905202FD58A9A1F7AA996EF2" genus="C." lsidName="C. hannoniae" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="hannoniae">
<emphasis id="12F100044908131F80E1E136B4EA70BA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">C. hannoniae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="25D2AA27CCAB84CD9BD55EB3861025EC" genus="C." lsidName="C. boosii" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="boosii">
<emphasis id="EF4A91782CEA900BFCB80AB90A1E0743" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">C. boosii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having cataphylls persisting 
<normalizedToken id="E6B3E460D45D5A34EB0BAE3A2A1EE148" originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
intact (vs. cataphylls ultimately deciduous or quickly deciduous) and the absence of bulbils.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
